        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>JACOB VOORSANGER&#44;<lb/>
                Box 319.<lb/></p>
            <p>Houston&#44; Texas&#44; Jan. 22 1883<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
                My dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>It is now nearly<lb/> a month since I received your last letter and<lb/> I feel as if I ought <del>to</del>  not to delay answering<lb/> any more.  First&#44; I am thankful for your praise of<lb/> the Visitor&#44; which since Jan. 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> has appeared ent<lb/>irely in a new form&#44; twice its former size&#44; with<lb/> a great deal of good and useful reading matter<lb/> in it.  I have commenced the publication of a<lb/> series of articles on &#34;Moses Mendelssohn&#34; and<lb/> the plan is to have them published in book<lb/> form as soon as completed.  This will constitute<lb/> the first of a series of Sabbath Visitor publications<lb/> destined for the use of schools and young people.<lb/>  Do you not think that the presentation of M&#39;s life<lb/> in a simple&#44; but attractive English form will<lb/> prove beneficial to our young people&#63;  I&#44; at least&#44;<lb/> hope so&#44; and besides&#44; I shall feel quite fond<lb/> to have my first book published.  I do not mean<lb/> to say that that is the height of my ambition<lb/> but I wish to contribute my share towards<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>JACOB VOORSANGER&#44;<lb/>
                Box 319.<lb/></p>
            <p>Houston&#44; Texas&#44; &#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;188<lb/></p>
            <p>supplying a want among the American Is<lb/>rael&#44; namely&#44; that of informing them of the<lb/> history of the fathers.  I have of late been thinking<lb/> of several matters&#44; which&#44; Heaven helping me&#44;<lb/> will take shape in book form.  I am still peg<lb/>ging away at my &#34;tales of Jewish family life&#34;<lb/> in Holland&#34; but i have deferred their publica<lb/>tion until my Mendelssohn series is finished.<lb/>  Then&#44; for the last twelve months&#44; I have been<lb/> quietly collecting materials for a book&#44; with<lb/> which I hope to make my reputation&#44; namely<lb/> &#34;a history of the Jews in America&#34; from <del>hist</del><lb/> discovery until this day&#44;&#34; but I can progress<lb/> but very&#44; very slowly.  The material is scanty<lb/> and what there is of it distributed over<lb/> nearly every point of the compass.  At some<lb/> future day I will ask your kind assist<lb/>ance in furnishing me prints concerning the<lb/> history of the Jews of Philadelphia&#44; which have<lb/> hitherto escaped my attention.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yesterday I received the three vols of the<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; with a very kind Hebrew postal card<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>JACOB VOORSANGER&#44;<lb/>
                Box 319.<lb/></p>
            <p>Houston&#44; Texas&#44; &#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;188<lb/></p>
            <p>&#40;3<lb/></p>
            <p>from Graeber I have the time neither to answer<lb/> the one nor to read the other but I must steal<lb/> me a few quiet evening hours very soon.  For the<lb/> last few days work has been impossible.  It<lb/> has been freezingly&#44; intensely cold&#44; and this<lb/> is actual distress in this climate.  My frame<lb/> is no more used to northern vigor and I have<lb/> suffered from the cold more than I ever expect<lb/>ed I would&#44; when for miles I was skating<lb/> on my native ice.  This letter bears evidence<lb/> of my writing it with cramped hands&#44; but<lb/> I must proceed&#44; as I have no time to idle<lb/> away any more.  If you permit&#44; I will&#44; after<lb/> perusing the letters&#44; try to popularize them<lb/> by a review in the Israelite.<lb/></p>
            <p>The matter discussed in our last letter<lb/> remains in <hi rend="underline">status quo</hi>.  The lady members<lb/> of the family are obdurate&#44; and I care<lb/> not to precipitate matters.  This is one<lb/> of the cases in which temporizing is a<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>JACOB VOORSANGER&#44;<lb/>
                Box 319.<lb/></p>
            <p>Houston&#44; Texas&#44; &#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;188<lb/></p>
            <p>&#40;4<lb/></p>
            <p>virtue.<lb/></p>
            <p>Have you heard of my Texas colleagues&#63;  If<lb/> not please advise me&#44; in which case I will<lb/> write them.<lb/></p>
            <p>I see from your last postal that you liked<lb/> my pamphlet.  I am glad of it&#44; as I was rather<lb/> anxious to know how it would be thought of<lb/> in the north.  Here around Jew and Gentile have<lb/> approved of it&#44; and even the members of<lb/> the offender&#39;s congregation&#44; the &#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/> in the city&#44; have expressed themselves as<lb/> on my side&#44; though they deplore the occur<lb/>rence.  I would be obliged if you could find<lb/> time to give me your opinion more elabor<lb/>ately.<lb/></p>
            <p>No other news at present.  I beg to be rem<lb/>embered to Miss Morais and the children<lb/> and awaiting an early reply I remain<lb/></p>
            <p>very truly yours<lb/>
                Jacob Voorsanger<lb/></p>
